{"id":"2304.00296","submitter":"Ignacio Ruiz","authors":"I. Ruiz Simo","title":"Center of mass momentum dependence of short-range correlations with the\n  coarse-grained Granada potential","comments":"29 pages, 11 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"nucl-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this work we study the effect of the angular average of the Pauli-blocking\noperator $Q$ of the Bethe-Goldstone equation on the relative high-momentum\ndistribution of correlated nucleon pairs in different configurations of total\nspin, $S=0,1$. To this end we solve the integral form of the Bethe-Goldstone\nequation in a partial wave expansion by using a coarse-grained nucleon-nucleon\npotential. The use of this kind of potentials reduces the problem to an\nalgebraic linear system of equations in coordinate representation that can be\nsolved by matrix inversion methods of, at most, 10x10 matrices for the coupled\npartial waves. This study is the natural extension of our previous one [1] for\nthe case where now the total momentum of the nucleon pair $K_{\\rm CM}$ is not\nzero. Our findings show that the high-momentum tail above $\\sim 2 k_F$ is not\naffected by the angular average of the Pauli-blocking operator nor by the value\nof the total momentum of the nucleon pair $K_{\\rm CM}$. This provides a\ntheoretical explanation of the factorization ansatz widely used in the\nliterature that assumes that the nucleon-pair momentum distributions,\n$n(\\mathbf{K}_{\\rm CM},\\mathbf{p})$ can be approximately given by the product\nof the momentum distribution of the center-of-mass and that of the relative\nmotion of the two-nucleon system, namely, $n(\\mathbf{K}_{\\rm\nCM},\\mathbf{p})\\simeq n_{\\rm CM}(\\mathbf{K}_{\\rm CM}) n_{\\rm rel}(\\mathbf{p})$,\nand it is also related to the universality of the short-range correlations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 1 Apr 2023 11:35:23 GMT"}],"updat